                  <p>If your wall heater doesn't turn on at all, follow these steps to troubleshoot the issue before considering a professional repair service like Same Day Appliance Repair:</p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>Check the Power Source: Ensure that the heater is properly plugged in or hardwired. If it's a plug-in model, make sure the plug is securely in the outlet. For hardwired units, verify that the circuit breaker hasn't tripped.</li>
                    <li>Inspect the Thermostat: Sometimes the issue can be as simple as an incorrectly set thermostat. Make sure the thermostat is set to a temperature higher than the current room temperature. Also, check if the thermostat itself is functioning properly.</li>
                    <li>Examine the Pilot Light: For gas wall heaters, ensure that the pilot light is lit. If it's not, follow the manufacturer's instructions to relight it. If the pilot light won't stay lit, this could indicate a problem with the thermocouple or gas supply.</li>
                    <li>Look for Obstructions: Check for any obstructions that might be blocking the heater's vents or airflow. Dust and debris can accumulate and prevent the heater from functioning correctly.</li>
                    <li>Test the Power Switch: Some heaters have an on/off switch. Make sure this switch is in the "on" position. Also, inspect the switch for any signs of damage or wear.</li>
                    <li>Check the Fuse or Circuit Breaker: If your heater is connected to a dedicated fuse or circuit breaker, make sure it hasn't blown or tripped. Replace the fuse or reset the breaker if necessary.</li>
                    <li>Inspect the Wiring: If you're comfortable doing so, inspect the wiring for any visible signs of damage or loose connections. Be sure to turn off the power to the heater at the circuit breaker before inspecting the wiring.</li>
